am’s Content preferences page. https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/HDwa_xCWhFBJ_OGHSW5jf-gmJ64=/0x0:1080x2400/1080x2400/filters:focal(540x1200:541x1201)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25366272/Screenshot_20240401_163712.png]\n[Image: Now you can choose whether or not to limit political content. https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/A991N2Da9AMbf4K6gMKMUTDiqy4=/0x0:1080x2400/1080x2400/filters:focal(540x1200:541x1201)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25366274/Screenshot_20240401_163640.png]\n\nAnd now you can expose yourself to as much political infighting as you want. The fact that you need to opt in to political opinions on a social network rather opting out may seem a little topsy-turvy, but this is apparently the way that the Meta execs felt safest. Whether this strategy really will make Threads a less contentious place — or whether it will just make it less interesting — is yet to be seen.\n"}],"package":null,"url":"https://www.theverge.com/24117988/threads-instagram-politics-how-to","commentsClosed":false,"railComponents":[{"__typename":"EntryRailNewsletter","entryRailNewsletter":{"name":"Verge Deals","slug":"deals"}}],"dek":{"plaintext":"While Meta is asking you to play it safe, you can still see the political battles if you want."},"leadImage":{"defaultImageUrl":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/r0sXTBkO2vCQbwF0YmHv33UxtnY=/0x0:3000x2000/1200x628/filters:focal(1500x1000:1501x1001)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25365556/HT055_THREADS_CVirginia.jpg","asset":{"title":"Vector collage showing various of aspects of using Threads.","contentType":"image/jpeg"}},"seoDescription":{"plaintext":"If you still want to get all the politics on Threads, you have to do it via Instagram."},"socialDescription":{"plaintext":"Get all the political posts that are fit or unfit to print."},"socialImage":null,"shouldUseHTMLNoindex":false,"shouldUseHTMLNofollow":false,"password":null,"additionalContributors":null,"_id":23882029,"leadComponent":{"__typename":"EntryLe